class SeatManager {
    int[] seats;
    int n;

    public SeatManager(int n) {
        this.n = n;
        seats = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            seats[i] = i + 1;
        }
    }

    public int reserve() {
        int minSeat = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (seats[i] != seats[minSeat] && seats[i] <= n && seats[i] >= 1) {
                minSeat = i;
            }
        }
        return minSeat;
    }

    public void unreserve(int seatNumber) {
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (seatNumber == seats[i]) {
                seats[i] = -1;
            }
        }
    }
}

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We create an array of size n to store the seat numbers and initialize them from 1 to n. In the reserve() method, we iterate through the array to find the seat with the smallest number that is not already reserved and not greater than n. We set the seatNumber to -1 to reserve it. In the unreserve(int seatNumber) method, we iterate through the array and check if the given seatNumber is already reserved. If so, we reserve it by setting its index in the array to -1.

The efficiency is high because we only iterate through the array once in both methods. The time complexity is O(n), where n is the number of seats. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single integer array. The energy implications are low because the algorithm does not consume any significant energy.

